{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532827"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:30:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:30:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14720"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14720","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14720"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.07,0.04,0.87,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111912"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7413"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14720"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2958"},{"type":"tags","id":"5585"},{"type":"tags","id":"8084"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45675"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111912"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute chest pain. She has a medical history of pre-diabetes, hypertension, and chronic kidney disease. Her estimated glomerular filtration rate is 29 mL/min/1.73m2 (\u0026gt;90). Her regular medications include paracetamol, perindopril, and furosemide. Two weeks prior she completed a course of oral amoxicillin for moderate upper respiratory infection with resolution of her symptoms at the time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe appears unwell and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her ECG shows ST-segment depression in leads V4-V6.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cardiology team recommends urgent coronary angiography.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors presents the highest risk for developing contrast-induced nephropathy in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pre-diabetes","Diuretic use","Recent oral amoxycillin","Chronic kidney disease","Hypertension"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has multiple risk factors for developing contrast-induced nephropathy (CIN), which is defined as an acute decline in renal function following the administration of iodinated contrast media. The condition typically manifests as an increase in serum creatinine by 25% or 44 \u00b5mol/L from baseline within 48-72 hours of contrast exposure.  Risk factors for CIN are diabetes mellitus, pre-existing renal function impairment, nephrotoxic drugs, congestive heart failure, dehydration, liver cirrhosis, prolonged hypotension, advanced age and multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E with reduced estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) is the most significant risk factor for developing CIN. The risk increases substantially when eGFR falls below 60 mL/min/1.73m2, and is particularly high with eGFR below 30 mL/min/1.73m2, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecent oral amoxycillin \u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to significantly impact the risk of CIN as the medication has been ceased.  Whilst penicillins can induce acute tubulointerstitial nephritis, sufficient time has passed for any potential nephrotoxic effects to resolve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E carries a lower risk compared to established diabetes mellitus, which itself is less significant than pre-existing chronic kidney disease. Pre-diabetes may indicate early metabolic dysfunction but has not yet caused significant vascular or renal changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E may contribute to the risk of CIN through its effects on renal vasculature and function, but it is not as significant a risk factor as chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiuretic use\u003C/strong\u003E can increase the risk of CIN through volume depletion, but this risk is modifiable through appropriate pre-procedure management including temporary cessation of the medication and adequate hydration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention strategies for high-risk patients include adequate pre-procedure hydration, minimising contrast volume, and considering alternative imaging modalities when possible. Temporary cessation of nephrotoxic medications  is also recommended.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple risk factors for contrast-induced nephropathy are often present in the same patient, increasing overall risk.","Prevention strategies should be implemented in high-risk patients before contrast administration."],"references":["Gleeson T, Bulugahapitiya S. Contrast-induced nepropathy.  American Journal of Roentgenology.  2004: 183 (6).  Available at: https://www.ajronline.org/doi/10.2214/ajr.183.6.01831673","Shams E, Mayrovitz HN. Contrast-Induced Nephropathy: A Review of Mechanisms and Risks. Cureus. 2021 May 4;13(5):e14842. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8174394/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14720"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}}